Note: ========================================
Note: x86-64 Assembly Parser
Note: ========================================
Note: Parser for x86-64 assembly language (AT&T syntax)
Note: Part of the Translation translation system
Note: Builds AST from token stream
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/x86/x86_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Constant ASM_INSTRUCTION as Integer is 1
Constant ASM_DIRECTIVE as Integer is 2
Constant ASM_LABEL as Integer is 3
Constant ASM_REGISTER as Integer is 4
Constant ASM_IMMEDIATE as Integer is 5
Constant ASM_MEMORY as Integer is 6
Constant ASM_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 7

@Reasoning:
Assembly statements (instructions, directives, labels, operands) are heterogeneous but every form has the same shape: a tag, an optional lexeme view, and a child list. A uniform node simplifies recursive memory operand parsing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four 8-byte fields: discriminator tag (ASM_INSTRUCTION/DIRECTIVE/LABEL/REGISTER/IMMEDIATE/MEMORY/IDENTIFIER), pointer to the lexeme bytes in the source buffer, lexeme length, and a children List.
@End Implementation

Type called "AsmNode":
    node_type as Integer
    value as Integer
    value_length as Integer
    children as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
The parser is a cursor over the lexer's token List; caching the token-list pointer at construction avoids dereferencing the lexer on every advance.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three 8-byte slots: backing lexer pointer, cached token-list pointer (copied from lexer offset 24), and the current token index.
@End Implementation

Type called "AsmParser":
    lexer as Integer
    tokens as Integer
    current as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Hoisting the lexer's token-list pointer into the parser struct keeps the per-token lookup tight (two loads instead of three).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate 24 bytes, store the lexer pointer, copy the token-list pointer from lexer offset 24 into parser offset 8, and initialise the cursor to 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_parser" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new parser from lexer

    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with 24
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, lexer
    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, tokens
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0
    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
The parser owns only its own 24-byte struct; the backing lexer and token storage are owned externally, so destruction is minimal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Deallocate the parser block; lexer and token list are untouched.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_parser" takes parser as Integer:
    Note: Free parser

    proc deallocate from Layout with parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
The parser builds an AST it hands to callers; when callers discard a subtree they need a single helper that recursively releases descendants and the children List.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-check the node; for each child in the children List recurse into destroy_asm_node, then dispose the List and the 32-byte node block.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in total descendant node count; one allocator deallocation per node and per child-List.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "destroy_asm_node" takes node as Integer:
    Note: Recursively free AST node and children

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        proc destroy_asm_node with child
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc destroy from List with children
    proc deallocate from Layout with node
End Process

@Reasoning:
The top-level driver materialises a synthetic root and gathers one statement per non-empty line; the root reuses the ASM_INSTRUCTION tag as a uniform envelope node that downstream consumers treat as the module container holding every statement as a sibling child.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Create the root node; loop fetching the current token, stopping on null or EOF (tag 0); skip standalone newlines (tag 13); otherwise call parse_statement and attach its result as a child.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in total token count; one allocation per statement plus its operands.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Consumes a tokenised view of untrusted assembly source; parse_statement and parse_operand discard unknown tokens to ensure termination.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "parse" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse entire assembly source into AST

    Let root be proc create_asm_node with ASM_INSTRUCTION, 0, 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc current_token with parser
        If token is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        If token_type is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Skip newlines
        If token_type is equal to 13:
            proc advance_token with parser
            Note: Continue to next token
        Otherwise:
            Let statement be proc parse_statement with parser
            If statement is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with root, statement
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return root
End Process

@Reasoning:
A single statement is exactly one of: directive (.foo), label ("name:"), instruction mnemonic, or a stray identifier. The first-token tag plus a 1-token lookahead for ":" is enough to dispatch.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the current token's type. Tag 3 (DIRECTIVE) -> parse_directive. Tag 14 (IDENTIFIER): if is_label_definition (next is ":") parse_label, otherwise treat as a bare identifier operand. Tag 1 (INSTRUCTION) -> parse_instruction. Any other tag triggers skip_to_newline as a recovery action and returns null.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Unknown tags drive skip_to_newline which is bounded by source length, preventing pathological inputs from looping.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "parse_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse a single assembly statement

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    Note: Parse directive
    If token_type is equal to 3:
        Return proc parse_directive with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse label or instruction
    If token_type is equal to 14:
        Note: Check if this is a label (next token is colon)
        Let is_label be proc is_label_definition with parser
        If is_label is equal to 1:
            Return proc parse_label with parser
        Otherwise:
            Note: Treat as instruction (e.g., jump target)
            Return proc parse_identifier_operand with parser
        End If
    End If

    Note: Parse instruction
    If token_type is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_instruction with parser
    End If

    Note: Unknown statement type - skip to next line
    proc skip_to_newline with parser
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
GAS directives are "Name args, args, ..." extending to end-of-line; building one ASM_DIRECTIVE node with operand children mirrors the instruction shape so later passes can iterate uniformly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Capture the directive lexeme into an ASM_DIRECTIVE node, advance past it, then loop calling parse_operand until newline or EOF, consuming optional comma separators between operands.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(k) in directive operand count; each operand allocates its own node.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "parse_directive" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse assembler directive

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let directive be proc create_asm_node with ASM_DIRECTIVE, value_ptr, value_length
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Parse directive arguments until newline
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc current_token with parser
        If current is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let current_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current, 0
        If current_type is equal to 13:  Note: Newline
            proc advance_token with parser
            Break
        End If

        If current_type is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Break
        End If

        Note: Parse directive argument
        Let arg be proc parse_operand with parser
        If arg is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with directive, arg
        End If

        Note: Handle comma separator
        Let comma_check be proc current_token with parser
        If comma_check is not equal to 0:
            Let comma_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with comma_check, 0
            If comma_type is equal to 7:
                proc advance_token with parser
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return directive
End Process

@Reasoning:
A label is "name:" followed by an optional same-line statement (rare in our supported subset); skipping the rest of the line keeps the label as a standalone node and avoids tangling label binding with the next statement.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Capture the identifier lexeme into an ASM_LABEL node, advance past the identifier, consume the colon (tag 12), then skip_to_newline to discard any trailing tokens.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_label" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse label definition

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let label be proc create_asm_node with ASM_LABEL, value_ptr, value_length
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Consume colon
    Let colon_token be proc current_token with parser
    If colon_token is not equal to 0:
        Let colon_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with colon_token, 0
        If colon_type is equal to 12:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If
    End If

    Note: Skip to newline
    proc skip_to_newline with parser

    Return label
End Process

@Reasoning:
Mnemonics carry zero or more comma-separated operands until end-of-line; the structural shape exactly matches parse_directive but the discriminator differs, so the loop is duplicated rather than parameterised.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Capture the mnemonic lexeme into an ASM_INSTRUCTION node and advance. Loop until newline or EOF: parse_operand, attach as child, consume optional comma.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(k) in operand count; bounded by source line length.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "parse_instruction" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse instruction with operands

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let instruction be proc create_asm_node with ASM_INSTRUCTION, value_ptr, value_length
    proc advance_token with parser

    Note: Parse operands until newline
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc current_token with parser
        If current is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let current_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current, 0
        If current_type is equal to 13:  Note: Newline
            proc advance_token with parser
            Break
        End If

        If current_type is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Break
        End If

        Note: Parse operand
        Let operand be proc parse_operand with parser
        If operand is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with instruction, operand
        End If

        Note: Handle comma separator
        Let comma_check be proc current_token with parser
        If comma_check is not equal to 0:
            Let comma_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with comma_check, 0
            If comma_type is equal to 7:
                proc advance_token with parser
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return instruction
End Process

@Reasoning:
AT&T operand forms are distinguishable by their leading token: '$' immediate, '%' register, '(' or leading number/identifier+'(' memory reference, bare identifier label-ref, bare number, or string.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Inspect the current token tag. 10 (DOLLAR) -> parse_immediate. 11 (PERCENT) -> parse_register. is_memory_operand returns true -> parse_memory. 14 (IDENTIFIER) -> parse_identifier_operand. 5 (NUMBER) -> parse_number_operand. 6 (STRING) -> parse_string_operand. Anything else: advance one token and return null so the caller resyncs.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Unknown leading tags advance exactly one position to guarantee forward progress on adversarial input.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "parse_operand" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse instruction operand

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    Note: Parse immediate value ($ prefix)
    If token_type is equal to 10:
        Return proc parse_immediate with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse register (% prefix)
    If token_type is equal to 11:
        Return proc parse_register with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse memory reference
    Let is_memory be proc is_memory_operand with parser
    If is_memory is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_memory with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse identifier (label reference)
    If token_type is equal to 14:
        Return proc parse_identifier_operand with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse number (direct number without $)
    If token_type is equal to 5:
        Return proc parse_number_operand with parser
    End If

    Note: Parse string
    If token_type is equal to 6:
        Return proc parse_string_operand with parser
    End If

    Note: Unknown operand - skip
    proc advance_token with parser
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
The '$' prefix marks an immediate value; the literal that follows is captured verbatim (numeric formatting validation belongs to the parser's downstream consumer).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skip the '$' sigil, read the next token's lexeme into an ASM_IMMEDIATE node, advance past it, and return.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_immediate" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse immediate value ($123)

    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip $

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let immediate be proc create_asm_node with ASM_IMMEDIATE, value_ptr, value_length
    proc advance_token with parser

    Return immediate
End Process

@Reasoning:
The '%' prefix marks a register; the bare name that follows (rax, rbx, eax, ...) is captured verbatim with downstream sub-register width determination deferred.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skip the '%' sigil, read the next token's lexeme into an ASM_REGISTER node, advance, and return.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_register" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse register (%rax, %rbx, etc.)

    proc advance_token with parser  Note: Skip %

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let register be proc create_asm_node with ASM_REGISTER, value_ptr, value_length
    proc advance_token with parser

    Return register
End Process

@Reasoning:
AT&T memory operands are "offset(%base, %index, scale)" with optional offset and optional ",index,scale" tail; positionally encoded children (offset, base, index, scale) make later code-generation lowering straightforward.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate an ASM_MEMORY node. If the current token is a number or identifier, parse it as the offset child. Consume '('. Parse the base register. If a comma follows, parse the index register; if another comma follows, parse the scale literal. Consume ')'.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) - at most four child operands are parsed.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "parse_memory" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse memory reference (offset(%base,%index,scale))

    Let memory be proc create_asm_node with ASM_MEMORY, 0, 0

    Note: Parse optional offset (number or identifier)
    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    If token_type is equal to 5:
        Let offset be proc parse_number_operand with parser
        proc add_child with memory, offset
    End If

    If token_type is equal to 14:
        Set offset to proc parse_identifier_operand with parser
        proc add_child with memory, offset
    End If

    Note: Expect lparen
    Let lparen be proc current_token with parser
    If lparen is not equal to 0:
        Let lparen_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lparen, 0
        If lparen_type is equal to 8:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If
    End If

    Note: Parse base register
    Let base_token be proc current_token with parser
    If base_token is not equal to 0:
        Let base_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with base_token, 0
        If base_type is equal to 11:
            Let base be proc parse_register with parser
            proc add_child with memory, base
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for comma (index register follows)
    Let comma1 be proc current_token with parser
    If comma1 is not equal to 0:
        Let comma1_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with comma1, 0
        If comma1_type is equal to 7:
            proc advance_token with parser

            Note: Parse index register
            Let index be proc parse_register with parser
            If index is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with memory, index
            End If

            Note: Check for comma (scale follows)
            Let comma2 be proc current_token with parser
            If comma2 is not equal to 0:
                Let comma2_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with comma2, 0
                If comma2_type is equal to 7:
                    proc advance_token with parser

                    Note: Parse scale
                    Let scale be proc parse_number_operand with parser
                    If scale is not equal to 0:
                        proc add_child with memory, scale
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Expect rparen
    Let rparen be proc current_token with parser
    If rparen is not equal to 0:
        Let rparen_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with rparen, 0
        If rparen_type is equal to 9:
            proc advance_token with parser
        End If
    End If

    Return memory
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bare identifiers appear as branch targets, symbol references, and directive arguments; tagging them ASM_IDENTIFIER lets the lowering stage resolve them against the symbol table later.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Capture the identifier lexeme into an ASM_IDENTIFIER node, advance one token, return.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_identifier_operand" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse identifier (label reference or symbol)

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let identifier be proc create_asm_node with ASM_IDENTIFIER, value_ptr, value_length
    proc advance_token with parser

    Return identifier
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bare numeric operands appear in directives (.long 42) and as memory-offset literals; the same ASM_IMMEDIATE shape used by '$N' is reused since downstream consumers only need the literal text.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Capture the numeric lexeme into an ASM_IMMEDIATE node, advance one token, return.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_number_operand" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse number operand

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let number be proc create_asm_node with ASM_IMMEDIATE, value_ptr, value_length
    proc advance_token with parser

    Return number
End Process

@Reasoning:
String operands appear in data-section directives (.ascii, .string). Capturing them as ASM_IDENTIFIER nodes (text-bearing leaves) defers actual escape interpretation to later passes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Capture the string lexeme - including its surrounding quotes - into an ASM_IDENTIFIER node, advance one token, return.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_string_operand" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse string operand

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let string_node be proc create_asm_node with ASM_IDENTIFIER, value_ptr, value_length
    proc advance_token with parser

    Return string_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Distinguishing a label "name:" from a bare identifier operand requires one-token lookahead for ':'; centralising the test keeps parse_statement's dispatch concise.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Bounds-check current+1 against the token list size; peek token at current+1 and return 1 if its tag is 12 (COLON), 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_label_definition" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current position is a label definition (identifier followed by colon)

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let current_index be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    If current_index plus 1 is greater than or equal to token_count:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let next_token be proc get from List with tokens, current_index plus 1
    Let next_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with next_token, 0

    If next_type is equal to 12:  Note: Colon
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Memory operands can start with a number (offset), an LPAREN (no offset, e.g. "(%rax)"), or a symbolic offset followed by LPAREN ("foo(%rax)"); positively identifying memory shape lets parse_operand avoid backtracking.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If the current tag is 5 (NUMBER) or 8 (LPAREN) return 1. If it is 14 (IDENTIFIER), peek current+1 and return 1 only when that next tag is 8 (LPAREN). Otherwise return 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_memory_operand" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current position starts a memory operand

    Let token be proc current_token with parser
    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    Note: Memory can start with number (offset) or lparen (no offset)
    If token_type is equal to 5:
        Return 1
    End If

    If token_type is equal to 8:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Memory can start with identifier (symbol + offset)
    If token_type is equal to 14:
        Note: Look ahead for lparen
        Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Let current_index be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
        Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

        If current_index plus 1 is less than token_count:
            Let next_token be proc get from List with tokens, current_index plus 1
            Let next_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with next_token, 0
            If next_type is equal to 8:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lookahead is the most frequent parser operation; bounding-checking inside the helper means every caller automatically gets a 0 sentinel on EOF without duplicating range checks.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read tokens pointer and cursor index. If the cursor is at or past the token-list size return 0. Otherwise return the List entry at the cursor index.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) with three memory loads and a List index access.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "current_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token without advancing

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let current be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    If current is greater than or equal to token_count:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc get from List with tokens, current
End Process

@Reasoning:
Token consumption happens at many call sites; isolating the cursor bump in one helper guarantees each accepted token advances the cursor exactly once.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the cursor index at parser offset 16, add one, store back.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance_token" takes parser as Integer:
    Note: Move to next token

    Let current be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, current plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
After a label or an unparseable statement, the parser resyncs to the next line so a single malformed statement does not derail subsequent statements.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loop fetching the current token; on null or EOF return; on newline (tag 13) advance past it and return; otherwise advance past it and continue.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Bounded by source line length and the token list size; guarantees forward progress on adversarial input.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "skip_to_newline" takes parser as Integer:
    Note: Skip tokens until newline or EOF

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc current_token with parser
        If token is equal to 0:
            Return
        End If

        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        If token_type is equal to 13:  Note: Newline
            proc advance_token with parser
            Return
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Return
        End If

        proc advance_token with parser
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Every node-producing parse_* helper goes through this constructor so the AsmNode layout (tag + lexeme view + children List) stays exactly defined in one site.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate 32 bytes, store node_type / value / value_length at offsets 0, 8, 16; create an empty children List and store it at offset 24.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_asm_node" takes node_type as Integer, value as Integer, value_length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new AST node

    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, value_length
    Let children be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, children
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Attaching a child requires touching the parent's children-List slot at offset 24; a tiny helper hides the layout offset and keeps the parse_* code readable.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the children-List pointer from offset 24 of the parent node and push the child node pointer onto it.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_child" takes parent as Integer, child as Integer:
    Note: Add child node to parent

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 24
    proc push from List with children, child
End Process
